top_5_pain_points (extracted from SalonGeek, YouTube comments, Reddit discussions, TikTok):

  1. THE BLOTCHY/PATCHY RESULT — Users repeatedly describe their sponge ombre coming out "blotchy," "spotty," or "uneven." Root cause: using too much polish on the sponge in one go, or not building up thin layers. This is the single most common failure point for beginners.

  2. POLISH DRYING TOO FAST ON THE SPONGE — Particularly with regular polish: users apply colour to sponge, by the time they dab the nail the polish has partially dried and won't blend. Leads to harsh lines instead of a gradient.

  3. GEL POLISH WON'T WORK WITH THE SPONGE METHOD — A very common confusion: beginners try the sponge technique with gel polish and get almost no colour transfer because gel stays in the sponge. Users don't realise gel requires a different technique (brush/blending method or specialised ombre brush).

  4. MASSIVE MESS ON SKIN AND CUTICLES — The sponge method transfers polish all over surrounding skin. Users find cleanup stressful and time-consuming, and don't know about liquid latex or peel-off base as a solution before starting.

  5. OMBRE CHIPS WITHIN 1–2 DAYS — Users frustrated that their at-home ombre fades or chips faster than regular nail polish. Usually caused by: skipping base coat, not capping the free edge, using a non-wipe top coat (too thin to fill sponge texture), or applying too many thick layers.

user_sentiment: Frustrated-but-aspiring — users know the look is achievable but feel let down by tutorials that make it look effortless without addressing what goes wrong.

